for_each creates multiple resource instances from a map or set of strings. Each instance has a stable KEY identity instead of a numeric index.

for_each with a set:
```hcl
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "data_zones" {
  for_each = toset(["raw", "curated", "processed"])
  bucket   = "mycompany-${each.key}"
}
# Instances: aws_s3_bucket.data_zones["raw"], ["curated"], ["processed"]
```

for_each with a map (richer configuration per item):
```hcl
variable "databases" {
  default = {
    airflow_meta = { engine = "postgres", size = "db.t3.medium" }
    dbt_results  = { engine = "postgres", size = "db.t3.large" }
    mlflow       = { engine = "mysql",    size = "db.t3.small" }
  }
}

resource "aws_db_instance" "de_databases" {
  for_each       = var.databases
  identifier     = each.key
  engine         = each.value.engine
  instance_class = each.value.size
}
```

for_each vs count:
- count: use for truly identical resources or on/off toggle (count = 0 or 1)
- for_each: use when resources differ by config OR when you need stable identifiers (removing an item does NOT shift other resources)

Interview tip: Prefer for_each over count in almost all real-world module design.
